This fixes short UTF-8 text detection. Fixes #56.
I guess the magic number 6 can avoid some wrong multibyte character detection, but it actually breaks short UTF-8 text detection. So I add a simple ratio condition to it.
By the way, `0.6` is another magic number...

Note: this can't fix such case:
```js
const UTF8Prober = require('./src/utf8prober');
function utf8test(str){
    let prober = (new UTF8Prober());
    prober.feed(Buffer.from(str).toString('binary'));
    console.log(prober.getConfidence());
}
utf8test("aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa中文");
// confidence is 0.7525
```
because the multibyte character ratio too low. LatinProber gives 0.95 confidence instead.

Maybe the proper way is ignore all ASCII characters? I am not sure.


Ref: https://github.com/microsoft/vscode/issues/33720

```js
// src.utf8prober.js
this.getConfidence = function() {
        var unlike = 0.99;
        if( this._mNumOfMBChar < 6 ) {
            for( var i = 0; i < this._mNumOfMBChar; i++ ) {
                unlike *= ONE_CHAR_PROB;
            }
            return 1 - unlike;
        } else {
            return unlike;
        }
    }
```
This magic number makes UTF-8 text shorter than 6 chars confidence never defeat others.

A simple fix is add multibytes chars ratio check.

See https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/33720

Test case
```
#!/bin/sh

foo() {
	echo "starting …"
}
```
Ellipsis symbol `…` makes vscode guess cp1252. UTF8 should have higher priority IMO

In [chardistribution.js](https://github.com/aadsm/jschardet/blob/master/src/chardistribution.js) line 246 through 248:
```js
if( aStr.charCodeAt(1) > 0x7F ) {
    order = -1;
}
```
According to [sjis encoding schemes](http://www.sljfaq.org/afaq/encodings.html#encodings-Encoding-schemes-for-Japanese-characters), [DBCS programming guide from Microsoft](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc194788.aspx) and [sjis encoding table](http://charset.7jp.net/sjis.html), we are interested in first  byte range: 0x81 -- 0x9f , 0xe0 -- 0xef, (the comment in line 235 is incorrect, the code in line 240 is correct), second byte range: **0x40 -- 0x7e,  0x80 -- 0xfc**(the comment in line 236 is incorrect, it should be 0x40 -- 0x7e, 0x80 -- 0xfc).

The code for the frequent Japanese character "の" is 0x82 0xcc, since second byte 0xcc  `aStr.charCodeAt(1)` is bigger than 0x7F , line 246 will return order = -1, hence missing it. It's order should be 328. 

line 246 through 248 should look like this:
```js
if( aStr.charCodeAt(1) < 0x40 || aStr.charCodeAt(1) === 0x7F || aStr.charCodeAt(1) > 0xFC) {`
    order = -1;
}
```

